  <!-- Approach / scenarios -->
  <section id="approach">
    <div class="section-card">
      <div class="section-kicker">Approach</div>
      <h2>How I Approach HR Problems</h2>
      <p>
        My starting point in any situation is to understand what is actually happening on the ground, then layer in policy, legislation, and internal precedents before recommending a path forward.
      </p>
      <div class="scenario-grid">
        <div class="scenario-card">
          <div class="scenario-badge">Scenario</div>
          <div class="scenario-title">Performance concerns with weak documentation</div>
          <p>
            A store manager wants to terminate a long‑service employee for “attitude and reliability” but offers only vague examples and limited written records.
          </p>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Questions &amp; information</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Ask for specific, recent examples of behaviour and impact on team or results.</li>
            <li>Review any prior coaching, PIPs, or warnings and timing of those conversations.</li>
            <li>Check attendance, schedule changes, and any accommodation history.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Policy &amp; framework</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Review progressive discipline and performance management policy, as well as human rights obligations if any protected grounds are in play.</li>
            <li>Consider internal precedents for similar cases and the organization’s risk tolerance.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Advisory stance</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>I would review applicable policy and internal precedents before recommending a path forward.</li>
            <li>Likely recommend structured coaching or a clear PIP with documented expectations and timelines, while flagging risks of jumping straight to termination.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="scenario-card">
          <div class="scenario-badge">Scenario</div>
          <div class="scenario-title">Complex leave &amp; accommodation request</div>
          <p>
            An employee with medical restrictions requests reduced hours and schedule changes that create gaps in coverage for peak times.
          </p>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Questions &amp; information</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Clarify functional restrictions, duration, and prognosis from current medical documentation.</li>
            <li>Ask the leader to outline specific operational impacts and what alternatives were explored.</li>
            <li>Map current staffing patterns and whether duties can be redistributed or scheduled differently.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Policy &amp; framework</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>I would consider local employment standards, human rights obligations, and any accommodation duties, alongside operational needs.</li>
            <li>Review leave and accommodation policy, disability management practices, and past accommodations in similar roles.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Advisory stance</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Work through options with the leader, making sure they understand the threshold for undue hardship, not just inconvenience.</li>
            <li>Align with LOA administrators and, where needed, Legal before recommending next steps or alternative roles or schedules.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="scenario-card">
          <div class="scenario-badge">Scenario</div>
          <div class="scenario-title">Policy‑practice gap discovered in the field</div>
          <p>
            During field conversations, you notice that managers have been following a long‑standing “rule of thumb” for leave duration that does not match written policy.
          </p>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Questions &amp; information</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Clarify how widespread the practice is and how long it has been in place.</li>
            <li>Identify who originally communicated the guidance and how it was interpreted by different leaders.</li>
            <li>Check for any employees who may already have been adversely affected.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Policy &amp; framework</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Review the written leave policy, employment standards, and any legal guidance related to the entitlement in question.</li>
            <li>Consult Benefits and HR leadership to confirm the correct interpretation and any historical decisions.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="scenario-sub">Advisory stance</div>
          <ul class="scenario-list">
            <li>Recommend a clear shift back to compliant practice, with an implementation plan and communication support for district and store leaders.</li>
            <li>Flag any past cases requiring remediation and work cross‑functionally to address them where appropriate.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

